        <p data-uuid="3e8b7160d2b2458798f463dd0fdc6f1f">
            “[There]
            is something very absurd in supporting a continent to be perpetually [forever]
            governed by an island.” This plainspoken argument against British rule over
            America appeared in <dfn title="Common Sense"><i>Common Sense</i></dfn>, a 47-page pamphlet that was distributed in
            Philadelphia in January 1776. <i>Common
            Sense</i> was published anonymously—that is, without the author’s name. The
            author, <b><dfn title="Paine, Thomas">Thomas Paine</dfn></b>, had
            recently emigrated to the colonies from Great Britain. He argued that citizens,
            not kings and queens, should make laws. At a time when monarchs ruled much of
            the world, this was a bold idea.</p>
        <figure class="image-with-caption vertical" data-uuid="1295d3ca697c454588bdbb4419d52fdd">
            <img alt="This photo shows a printed page from Thomas Paine's Common Sense." data-uuid="a29d6840b14647c585be4a0012274b75" src="../../img/module_4_lesson03/8_snlese454170_709p.jpg" />
            <div class="figcaption" data-uuid="48b3031fef684af99d260ad6b293a24f">
                <p class="caption" data-uuid="ac0026c5d9734828956be2b56246c713">
                    In <i>Common
                    Sense</i>, Thomas Paine argued that the colonies should claim their independence.
                </p>
            </div>
        </figure>
        <p data-uuid="713ef139cd62420a817b196d54d23d40">News of the work spread throughout the colonies,
            eventually selling some 500,000 copies. Paine reached a wide audience by
            writing as a common person speaking to common people. He used loaded language
            to influence people’s opinions. Loaded language is powerful words and phrases
            used to persuade people by appealing to their emotions. <i>Common Sense</i> changed the way many colonists viewed their king. It
            made a strong case for economic freedom in the colonies and for the right to
            military self-defense. It cried out against tyranny—that is, the abuse of
            government power. Thomas Paine’s words rang out in his time, and they have
            echoed throughout American history.<br />
        </p>
